	</form></div><span class="pb doctop" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-15-02-pb-0392">392<a style="padding-left: 5px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-15/ADMS-06-15-02-pb-0392.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a></span><div class="doc">
        
        <h1>From C. W. F. Dumas</h1>
        <div class="docbody" xml:lang="fr">
          <div class="opener"><table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Monsieur</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Lahaie 5<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">e.</span> Dec. 1783</td>
	      </tr>
      </table></div>
          <p>Jai le plaisir de remarquer, par lhonore vtre du 28<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">e.</span> Nov., que nous avons pens &amp; crit lun a lautre le mme jour. Nous sentons &amp; partageons sincerement la joie que vous aurez dembrasser bien-tt Mad<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">e.</span> Adams &amp; vos chers Enfans, que nous supposons venir aussi. Mon Epouse, ainsi que ma fille, languit de lui rendre leurs <span class="pb" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-15-02-pb-0393">[393<a style="padding-left: 0px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-15/ADMS-06-15-02-pb-0393.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a>]</span>devoirs; &amp; la premiere sempressera de lui remettre tous les Dpts que vous avez laisss entre ses mains ici.</p>
          <p>Come je ne vois par votre Lettre, Monsieur, si vous resterez avec Madame tout de bon  Lahaie, ni par consquent si vous voulez avoir lhtel entier  votre disposition &amp;  la sienne au mois de May prochain, &amp; quil mimporte cependant de prendre les arrangemens les moins ruineux pour trouvert un autre couvert pour nous, je vous demande en grace, Monsieur, de me faire au plutt connotre clairement toutes vos intentions  cet gard, afin que je prenne mon parti l-dessus  votre satisfaction, &amp; sans trop de perte &amp; dinconvniens pour nous: car cest aux environs du nouvel an, come jai dj eu lhonneur de vous en parler dans une autre Lettre, quon loue les maisons ici, pour les occuper au mois de May: alors on peut choisir ce qui convient; autrement il faut payer le double, pour tre trs mal  son aise</p>
          <p>Lon est indign ici, &amp; lon doit ltre aussi en france, de la raison pitoyable allgue par le D de Mr  Versailles, pour ne pas finir la paix  Paris. Ils appellent cette raison une impudente fausset; &amp; lon va prendre ici des rsolutions en consquence.<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-15-02-0196-fn-0001" id="ADMS-06-15-02-0196-fn-0001-ptr">1</a></p>
          <p>Au cas que vous vous proposassiez, Monsieur, de passer lhiver ici avec Madame Adams, souhaitez-vous que mon Epouse fasse votre provision de tourbes, pendant que les Canaux seront encore ouverts; car aprs cela on doit en payer cher de mauvaises. En ce cas faites-nous s. v. p. savoir combien de cent tonneaux vous en voulez.</p>
          <p>Mr. Fagel, que jai vu au cercle, ma charg de ses complimens pour vous. M<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">r.</span> De Gyzelaer, avec les siens, ma pri de vous faite part de son union prochaine, dans 2 ou 3 mois avec une aimable Demoiselle.<a class="ptr" href="#ADMS-06-15-02-0196-fn-0002" id="ADMS-06-15-02-0196-fn-0002-ptr">2</a></p>
          <p>Ma famille vous prsente ses respects, &amp; bien leurs complimens  Mr. votre fils ainsi que les miens.</p>
          <p>Je suis avec grand respect, De Votre Exc<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">e.</span> / Le trs-humble &amp; trs obissant serviteur</p>
          <div class="closer"><p class="signed">C.w.f. Dumas</p></div>
        </div>
        <div class="translation">
          <h2><span class="hi-all-small-caps" style="font-variant: small-caps; text-transform: lowercase;">Translation</span></h2>
          <div class="opener"><table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Sir</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">The Hague, 5 December 1783</td>
	      </tr>
      </table></div>
          <p>I have the pleasure of noting, from your esteemed letter of 28 November, that we thought of and wrote to each other on the same day. We feel and sincerely share the joy that you will experience in embracing Mrs. Adams and your dear children, who we suppose are also coming. My wife and <span class="pb" title="page number in print edition" id="ADMS-06-15-02-pb-0394">[394<a style="padding-left: 0px" onclick="window.open('/img-document-get.xqy?image=ADMS/Pages/ADMS-06-15/ADMS-06-15-02-pb-0394.jpg', 'pageImage', 'scrollbars=1,resizable=1'); return false" onkeypress="this.onclick();" tabindex="0" title="Click to view image of page from print edition"><img src="/img-ML/page-icon.gif" width="18" height="20" style="vertical-align:middle;" alt="page icon"/></a>]</span>my daughter look forward to paying their respects to her, and the former will hurry to give to her all that you deposited here in her hands.</p>
          <p>As I cannot tell from your letter, sir, if you are planning to reside with madame right here at The Hague, nor consequently if you want the whole house at your disposal and hers this coming May, and as it is important meanwhile that I make the least ruinous arrangements to find another dwelling for us, I ask you please, sir, to let me know clearly all your intentions in this matter as soon as possible, so that I can make my decision in this regard in a way that meets your needs, and without too much loss and inconvenience for us, because it is around New Years, as I had the honor of informing you in another letter, that houses are rented here for occupancy in the month of May. Then one can choose something serviceable. Otherwise you have to pay twice the price, only to be very uncomfortable.</p>
          <p>Everyone is indignant here, as they must also be in France, at the pitiful reason put forward by the Duke of Manchester at Versailles for why the peace has not yet been concluded at Paris. They call this reason an impudent falsehood, and they are going to make resolutions here as a consequence.<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">1</span></p>
          <p>If you intend, sir, to spend the winter here with Mrs. Adams, would you like my wife to acquire the peat for you while the canals are still open, because after that you have to pay a high price for poor quality. In that case please let us know how many hundreds of barrels you want of it.</p>
          <p>Mr. Fagel, whom I saw on my rounds, asked me to send his compliments to you. Mr. de Gyselaar, while sending his own, begged me to inform you of his upcoming union, in two or three months, with a fine young lady.<span class="hi-super" style="font-size: 80%; line-height: 0.8; vertical-align: super;">2</span></p>
          <p>My family sends you their respects as well as their compliments to your esteemed son, and please add my own.</p>
          <p>I am with great respect, your excellencys very humble and very obedient servant</p>
          <div class="closer"><p class="signed">C.w.f. Dumas</p></div>
        </div>
        <div class="docback">
          <div class="note-source" id="ADMS-06-15-02-0196-sn">
   <p><abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ recipients copy (A recipients copy is assumed to be in the hand of the signer unless it is otherwise described.) ]">RC</abbr> (Adams Papers); internal address: Londres  S. E. Mr. Adams, M. P.</p>
</div>
          <div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#ADMS-06-15-02-0196-fn-0001-ptr" id="ADMS-06-15-02-0196-fn-0001">1</a>
   <p>Following the exchange of copies of the ratified Anglo-Dutch preliminary peace treaty, the Duke of Manchester informed the Dutch negotiators, Mattheus Lestevenon van Berkenrode and Gerard Brantsen, that Britain wished the negotiations for the definitive treaty to be held at either London or The Hague rather than Paris. The British diplomat gave no reason for the change, although it may be surmised that it was to be rid of any French influence on the negotiations. In Jan. 1784, following the lead of the States of Holland, the States General refused to agree to the British proposal, since it already had ministers at Paris (<span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Gazette dAmsterdam</span>, 9 Dec. 1783, 6 Jan. 1784; <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ &lt;i&gt;The Diplomatic Correspondence of the United States of America, from . . . 1783, to . . . 1789&lt;/i&gt;, [[ed. William A. Weaver]], repr., Washington, 1837 [[actually 1855]]; 3 vols. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Dipl. Corr., 17831789</span></span>, 3:478).</p>
</div>
          
          <div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#ADMS-06-15-02-0196-fn-0002-ptr" id="ADMS-06-15-02-0196-fn-0002">2</a>
   <p>Cornelis de Gyselaar married Catharina Geertruida Heerega at The Hague on 1 Feb. 1784 (<span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ P. C. Molhuysen and others, eds., &lt;i&gt;Nieuw Nederlandsch Biografisch Woordenboek&lt;/i&gt;, Leyden, 19111937; 10 vols. ]"><span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Nieuw Ned. Biog. Woordenboek</span></span>, 10:309310).</p>
</div>
          
